The Zerodha trading dashboard needs to show: 'Total volume traded for TCS in the last 5 minutes'. With @KafkaListener:

```java
// Option A: @KafkaListener + DB query (WRONG approach):
@KafkaListener(topics="trade-executed")
void handle(TradeExecutedEvent e) {
    db.insert(e);  // save every trade
}

// Dashboard API:
@GetMapping("/volume/TCS")
double getVolume() {
    return db.sum("SELECT SUM(total) FROM trades WHERE symbol='TCS'
                   AND executed_at > NOW() - INTERVAL 5 MINUTES");
    // Problem: this runs on EVERY dashboard refresh (100s/second)!
    // Problem: result is stale the moment you execute it
}
```

**With Kafka Streams:**
```java
// The answer is ALWAYS ready — Kafka Streams maintains it continuously:
@Bean
public KStream<String, TradeExecutedEvent> buildStreamsTopology(
        StreamsBuilder builder) {

    builder.stream("trade-executed", Consumed.with(stringSerde, tradeSerde))
        .groupBy((key, event) -> event.symbol())       // group by stock symbol
        .windowedBy(TimeWindows.ofSizeWithNoGrace(
            Duration.ofMinutes(5)))                    // 5-minute window
        .aggregate(
            () -> 0.0,                                 // init
            (sym, event, total) -> total + event.totalValue())
        .toStream()
        .to("trade-volume-5min");                      // result always up-to-date

    return null;
}

// Dashboard API (now INSTANT — no DB query):
@GetMapping("/volume/{symbol}")
double getVolume(@PathVariable String symbol) {
    return stateStore.get(symbol);  // pre-computed by Kafka Streams!
}
```

The volume is maintained continuously by Kafka Streams as trades arrive. The dashboard reads a pre-computed result. No DB query. No staleness. Real-time.

